ilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Schotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1227–Aft 1285":"1227–after 1285","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1227–1285":"1227–1285","1237–Female":"1237–Deceased","1267–Male":"1267–Deceased","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1189–1228":"1189–1228","1228":"1228","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","1237":"1237","1225":"1225","1267":"1267","1189":"1189","1298":"1298","1285":"1285","1262":"1262","Aft 1285":"after 1285","1180":"1180","Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Walter de Berkeley - First Laird of Kilbirnie was born in 1227, in Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland, his father, Roger de Berkeley, was 48 and his mother, Margaret de Marshal, was 38. He married Margaret de Craufurd in 1262, in Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1285, in Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1227–Aft 1285":"1227–pärast 1285","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1227–1285":"1227–1285","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","1267–Male":"1267–Surnud","1180–1226":"1180–1226","1189–1228":"1189–1228","1228